{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}} {{infobox book | | name = Sense of place | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = Cover of 1st edition | author = [[George Seddon (academic)|George Seddon]] | cover_artist = | country = Australia | language = English | series = | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[University of Western Australia Press]] | release_date = 1972 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 274 | isbn = 0-85564-058-8 | oclc= 495902 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Sense of place: a response to an environment: the Swan Coastal Plain, Western Australia''''' is a 1972 book by [[George Seddon (academic)|George Seddon]]. It documents Seddon's struggle to understand the [[Swan Coastal Plain]], a biogeographic region that he initially found harsh and unwelcoming. It includes information on [[landform]]s, [[climate]], [[geology]], [[soil]]s, [[flora]], the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]], the coast, offshore islands, [[wetland]]s, and urban areas. This information is, however, essentially presented in a literary style; in the words of Mark Tredinnick: "This is the kind of geography an essayist writes. This is the kind of essay a literate scientist writes. This is a literary natural history."
In Australia it is considered a landmark environmental publication. Among its claims to influence is having given modern currency to the term ''[[sense of place]]''. Although Seddon did not coin the phrase, it was this book that introduced the phrase into the fields of [[landscape design|landscape]] and [[environmental design]].
